<item>
 <title>4 Lessons on Scaling Up Sustainable Transport in US and Chinese Cities</title>
 <link>http://www.chinafaqs.org/blog-posts/4-lessons-scaling-sustainable-transport-us-and-chinese-cities</link>
 <description>&lt;div class=&quot;field field-type-filefield field-field-image&quot;&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;
            &lt;div class=&quot;field-item odd&quot;&gt;
                    &lt;img src=&quot;http://www.chinafaqs.org/files/chinainfo/imagecache/news-image/China%20biking.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; title=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;160&quot; height=&quot;120&quot; class=&quot;imagecache imagecache-news-image imagecache-default imagecache-news-image_default&quot;/&gt;        &lt;/div&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;field field-type-text field-field-author&quot;&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;
            &lt;div class=&quot;field-item odd&quot;&gt;
                    Lulu Xue        &lt;/div&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;This post &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.wri.org/blog/2016/06/4-lessons-scaling-sustainable-transport-us-and-chinese-cities&quot;&gt;originally appeared&lt;/a&gt; on WRI&amp;rsquo;s insights blog.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Transportation is already a major source of CO2 emissions in both &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.eia.gov/environment/emissions/carbon&quot; /&gt;China and the United States—at 20 percent and 30 percent, respectively&lt;/a&gt;. The percentage of people traveling by car is increasing in Chinese cities, rising from 15 percent to 34 percent in Beijing between 2002 and 2013, creating air pollution and fueling climate change.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.chinafaqs.org/blog-posts/4-lessons-scaling-sustainable-transport-us-and-chinese-cities&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;read more&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
